When you mention `@gitcommit.mdc`, the system will help you commit and push automatically.

### Automatic Options:

**Option 1: Git Hook (Automatic)**
After every `git commit`, you'll be prompted to:
- Set up remote repository URL (if not configured)
- Push to remote automatically

**Option 2: Auto-Push Script**
```bash
./scripts/auto-push.sh "your commit message"
```
This will:
- Stage all changes
- Commit with your message
- Ask for repository URL if not set
- Push to remote automatically

**Option 3: Manual Push**
```bash
git push -u origin main
```

### Setting up remote (if not configured):
```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/repo.git
```

**Note**: The post-commit hook will automatically prompt you for the repository URL if it's not configured, then ask if you want to push.
